    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The area <m>A</m> enclosed by a square, in square inches,
          is a function of the length of one of its sides <m>x</m>,
          when measured in inches.
          This relation is expressed by the formula <m>A(x) = x^2</m> for <m>x > 0</m>.
          Find <m>A(3)</m> and solve <m>A(x) = 36</m>.
          Interpret your answers to each.
          Why is <m>x</m> restricted to <m>x > 0</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>A(3) = 9</m>,
          so the area enclosed by a square with a side of length <m>3</m> inches is <m>9</m> square inches.
          The solutions to <m>A(x) = 36</m> are <m>x = \pm 6</m>.
          Since <m>x</m> is restricted to <m>x > 0</m>,
          we only keep <m>x = 6</m>.
          This means for the area enclosed by the square to be <m>36</m> square inches,
          the length of the side needs to be <m>6</m> inches.
          Since <m>x</m> represents a length, <m>x > 0</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
