          The area <m>A</m> enclosed by a circle, in square meters,
          is a function of its radius <m>r</m>, when measured in meters.
          This relation is expressed by the formula <m>A(r) = \pi r^2</m> for <m>r > 0</m>.
          Find <m>A(2)</m> and solve <m>A(r) = 16\pi</m>.
          Interpret your answers to each.
          Why is <m>r</m> restricted to <m>r > 0</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>A(2) = 4\pi</m>,
          so the area enclosed by a circle with radius <m>2</m> meters is <m>4\pi</m> square meters.
          The solutions to <m>A(r) = 16\pi</m> are <m>r = \pm 4</m>.
          Since <m>r</m> is restricted to <m>r > 0</m>,
          we only keep <m>r = 4</m>.
          This means for the area enclosed by the circle to be <m>16\pi</m> square meters,
          the radius needs to be <m>4</m> meters.
          Since <m>r</m> represents a radius (length), <m>r > 0</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
